# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electronic-filter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] An **active filter** is a type of analog circuit implementing an electronic filter using active components, typically an amplifier.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Amplifiers included in a filter design can be used to improve the cost, performance and predictability of a filter.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] An amplifier prevents the load impedance of the following stage from affecting the characteristics of the filter.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] An active filter can have complex poles and zeros without using a bulky or expensive inductor.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] The shape of the response, the Q (quality factor), and the tuned frequency can often be set with inexpensive variable resistors.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] In some active filter circuits, one parameter can be adjusted without affecting the others.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Using active elements has some limitations.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Basic filter design equations neglect the finite bandwidth of amplifiers.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Available active devices have limited bandwidth, so they are often impractical at high frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Amplifiers consume power and inject noise into a system.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Certain circuit topologies may be impractical if no DC path is provided for bias current to the amplifier elements.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Power handling capability is limited by the amplifier stages.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Active filters can implement the same transfer functions as passive filters.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] where most of the offending rumble comes from a particular frequency).
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] An active filter can have gain, increasing the power available in a signal compared to the input.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Passive filters dissipate energy from a signal and cannot have a net power gain.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] This advantage may not be as important for active filters entirely integrated on a chip because the available capacitors have relatively low values and so require high value resistors which take up area of the integrated circuit.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Active filters have good isolation between stages, and can provide high input impedance and low output impedance; this makes their characteristics independent of the source and load impedances.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Multiple stages can be cascaded when desired to improve characteristics.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] In contrast, design of multiple-stage passive filters must take into account each stage's frequency-dependent loading of the preceding stage.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] It is feasible to make active filters tunable over a wide range, compared with passive filters.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Since inductors are not used, filters can be made in a very compact size and do not produce or interact with magnetic fields that may be present.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] Compared with active filters, passive filters require no additional power supplies.
[src:electronic-filter/active-filter] The amplifying devices of an active filter must provide predictable gain and performance over the entire frequency range to be processed; the gain–bandwidth product of the amplifier will constrain the maximum frequency that can be used.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] An **all-pass filter** is a signal processing filter that passes all frequencies equally in gain, but changes the phase relationship among various frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] Most types of filter reduce the amplitude (i.e. the magnitude) of the signal applied to it for some values of frequency, whereas the all-pass filter allows all frequencies through without changes in level.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] A common application in electronic music production is in the design of an effects unit known as a "phaser", where a number of all-pass filters are connected in sequence and the output mixed with the raw signal.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] It does this by varying its phase shift as a function of frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] Generally, the filter is described by the frequency at which the phase shift crosses 90° (i.e., when the input and output signals go into quadrature – when there is a quarter wavelength of delay between them).
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] They are generally used to compensate for other undesired phase shifts that arise in the system, or for mixing with an unshifted version of the original to implement a notch comb filter.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] They may also be used to convert a mixed phase filter into a minimum phase filter with an equivalent magnitude response or an unstable filter into a stable filter with an equivalent magnitude response.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The operational amplifier circuit shown in adjacent figure implements a single-pole active all-pass filter that features a low-pass filter at the non-inverting input of the opamp.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] which has one pole at -1/RC and one zero at 1/RC (i.e., they are *reflections* of each other across the imaginary axis of the complex plane).
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The filter has unity-gain magnitude for all ω.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The filter introduces a different delay at each frequency and reaches input-to-output *quadrature* at ω=1/RC (i.e., phase shift is 90°).
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] This implementation uses a low-pass filter at the non-inverting input to generate the phase shift and negative feedback.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] In fact, the phase shift of the all-pass filter is double the phase shift of the low-pass filter at its non-inverting input.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] where T is the delay (in seconds) and $s\in \mathbb {C}$ is complex frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] where the last step was achieved via a first-order Taylor series expansion of the numerator and denominator.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] By setting $RC=T/2$ we recover $H(s)$ from above.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The operational amplifier circuit shown in the adjacent figure implements a single-pole active all-pass filter that features a high-pass filter at the non-inverting input of the opamp.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The filter introduces a different delay at each frequency and reaches input-to-output *quadrature* at ω=1/RC (i.e., phase lead is 90°).
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] This implementation uses a high-pass filter at the non-inverting input to generate the phase shift and negative feedback.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] In fact, the phase shift of the all-pass filter is double the phase shift of the high-pass filter at its non-inverting input.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The resistor can be replaced with a FET in its *ohmic mode* to implement a voltage-controlled phase shifter; the voltage on the gate adjusts the phase shift.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] In electronic music, a phaser typically consists of two, four or six of these phase-shifting sections connected in tandem and summed with the original.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] A low-frequency oscillator (LFO) ramps the control voltage to produce the characteristic swooshing sound.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The benefit to implementing all-pass filters with active components like operational amplifiers is that they do not require inductors, which are bulky and costly in integrated circuit designs.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] In other applications where inductors are readily available, all-pass filters can be implemented entirely without active components.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] There are a number of circuit topologies that can be used for this.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The following are the most commonly used circuits.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The **lattice phase equaliser**, or **filter**, is a filter composed of lattice, or X-sections.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] With single element branches it can produce a phase shift up to 180°, and with resonant branches it can produce phase shifts up to 360°.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The filter is an example of a constant-resistance network (i.e., its image impedance is constant over all frequencies).
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The phase equaliser based on T topology is the unbalanced equivalent of the lattice filter and has the same phase response.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] While the circuit diagram may look like a low pass filter it is different in that the two inductor branches are mutually coupled.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] This results in transformer action between the two inductors and an all-pass response even at high frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The bridged T topology is used for delay equalisation, particularly the differential delay between two landlines being used for stereophonic sound broadcasts.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] This application requires that the filter has a linear phase response with frequency (i.e., constant group delay) over a wide bandwidth and is the reason for choosing this topology.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] which has a zero at $1/{\overline {z_{0}}}$ , where ${\overline {z}}$ denotes the complex conjugate.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The pole and zero sit at the same angle but have reciprocal magnitudes (i.e., they are *reflections* of each other across the boundary of the complex unit circle).
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] The placement of this pole-zero pair for a given $z_{0}$ can be rotated in the complex plane by any angle and retain its all-pass magnitude characteristic.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] Complex pole-zero pairs in all-pass filters help control the frequency where phase shifts occur.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] where $y[k]$ is the output and $x[k]$ is the input at discrete time step k .
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] Filters such as the above can be cascaded with unstable or mixed-phase filters to create a stable or minimum-phase filter without changing the magnitude response of the system.
[src:electronic-filter/all-pass-filter] For example, by proper choice of $z_{0}$ , a pole of an unstable system that is outside of the unit circle can be canceled and reflected inside the unit circle.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] An **analogue filter** is a basic building block of signal processing much used in electronics.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Passive linear electronic analogue filters are those filters which can be described with linear differential equations (linear); they are composed of capacitors, inductors and, sometimes, resistors (passive) and are designed to operate on continuously varying analogue signals.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] There are many linear filters which are not analogue in implementation (digital filter), and there are many electronic filters which may not have a passive topology – both of which may have the same transfer function of the filters described in this article.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Analogue filters are most often used in wave filtering applications, that is, where it is required to pass particular frequency components and to reject others from analogue (continuous-time) signals.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Analogue filters have played an important part in the development of electronics.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Especially in the field of telecommunications, filters have been of crucial importance in a number of technological breakthroughs and have been the source of enormous profits for telecommunications companies.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] It should come as no surprise, therefore, that the early development of filters was intimately connected with transmission lines.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Transmission line theory gave rise to filter theory, which initially took a very similar form, and the main application of filters was for use on telecommunication transmission lines.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] However, the arrival of network synthesis techniques greatly enhanced the degree of control of the designer.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Wherever possible, and especially at low frequencies, analogue filters are now implemented in a filter topology which is active in order to avoid the wound components (i.e., inductors, transformers, etc.) required by passive topology.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] It is possible to design linear analogue mechanical filters using mechanical components which filter mechanical vibrations or acoustic waves.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] While there are few applications for such devices in mechanics per se, they can be used in electronics with the addition of transducers to convert to and from the electrical domain.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Indeed, some of the earliest ideas for filters were acoustic resonators because the electronics technology was poorly understood at the time.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] In principle, the design of such filters can be achieved entirely in terms of the electronic counterparts of mechanical quantities, with kinetic energy, potential energy and heat energy corresponding to the energy in inductors, capacitors and resistors, respectively.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Image filter theory grew out of transmission line theory, and the design proceeded in a similar manner to transmission line analysis.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] For the first time, filters could be produced that had precisely controllable passbands and other parameters.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] These developments took place in the 1920s, and filters produced to these designs were still in widespread use in the 1980s, only declining as the use of analogue telecommunications has declined.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Their immediate application was the economically important development of frequency division multiplexing for use on intercity and international lines.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The mathematical bases of network synthesis were laid in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] After World War II, network synthesis became the primary tool of filter design.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Network synthesis put filter design on a firm mathematical foundation, freeing it from the mathematically sloppy techniques of image design and severing the connection with physical lines.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The essence of network synthesis is that it produces a design that will (at least if implemented with ideal components) accurately reproduce the response originally specified in black box terms.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Throughout this article, the letters R, L, and C are used with their usual meanings to represent resistance, inductance, and capacitance, respectively.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] In particular, they are used in combinations, such as LC, to mean, for instance, a network consisting only of inductors and capacitors.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Z is used for electrical impedance, any 2-terminal combination of RLC elements and in some sections D is used for the rarely seen quantity elastance, which is the inverse of capacitance.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Early filters utilised the phenomenon of resonance to filter signals.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Although electrical resonance had been investigated by researchers from a very early stage, it was at first not widely understood by electrical engineers.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Consequently, the much more familiar concept of acoustic resonance (which in turn, can be explained in terms of the even more familiar mechanical resonance) found its way into filter design ahead of electrical resonance.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Resonance can be used to achieve a filtering effect because the resonant device will respond to frequencies at, or near, the resonant frequency but will not respond to frequencies far from resonance.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Hence, frequencies far from resonance are filtered out from the output of the device.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Resonance was noticed early on in experiments with the Leyden jar, invented in 1746.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The Leyden jar stores electricity due to its capacitance, and is, in fact, an early form of a capacitor.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] When a Leyden jar is discharged by allowing a spark to jump between the electrodes, the discharge is oscillatory.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This was not suspected until 1826, when Felix Savary in France, and later (1842) Joseph Henry in the US noted that a steel needle placed close to the discharge does not always magnetise in the same direction.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] They both independently drew the conclusion that there was a transient oscillation dying with time.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Hermann von Helmholtz in 1847 published his important work on conservation of energy in part of which he used those principles to explain why the oscillation dies away, that it is the resistance of the circuit which dissipates the energy of the oscillation on each successive cycle.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Helmholtz also noted that there was evidence of oscillation from the electrolysis experiments of William Hyde Wollaston.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Wollaston was attempting to decompose water by electric shock, but found that both hydrogen and oxygen were present at both electrodes.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] In normal electrolysis, they would separate, one to each electrode.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Helmholtz explained why the oscillation decayed, but he had not explained why it occurred in the first place.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This was left to Sir William Thomson (Lord Kelvin), who, in 1853, postulated that there was inductance present in the circuit as well as the capacitance of the jar and the resistance of the load.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This established the physical basis for the phenomenon – the energy supplied by the jar was partly dissipated in the load but also partly stored in the magnetic field of the inductor.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] So far, the investigation had been on the natural frequency of transient oscillation of a resonant circuit resulting from a sudden stimulus.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] More important from the point of view of filter theory is the behaviour of a resonant circuit when driven by an external AC signal: there is a sudden peak in the circuit's response when the driving signal frequency is at the resonant frequency of the circuit.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] James Clerk Maxwell heard of the phenomenon from Sir William Grove in 1868 in connection with experiments on dynamos, and was also aware of the earlier work of Henry Wilde in 1866.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Maxwell explained resonance mathematically, with a set of differential equations, in much the same terms that an RLC circuit is described today.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Heinrich Hertz (1887) experimentally demonstrated the resonance phenomena by building two resonant circuits, one of which was driven by a generator and the other was tunable and only coupled to the first electromagnetically (i.e., no circuit connection).
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Hertz showed that the response of the second circuit was at a maximum when it was in tune with the first.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The diagrams produced by Hertz in this paper were the first published plots of an electrical resonant response.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] As mentioned earlier, it was acoustic resonance that inspired filtering applications, the first of these being a telegraph system known as the "harmonic telegraph".
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Versions are due to Elisha Gray, Alexander Graham Bell (1870s), Ernest Mercadier and others.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Its purpose was to simultaneously transmit a number of telegraph messages over the same line and represents an early form of frequency division multiplexing (FDM).
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] FDM requires the sending end to transmit at different frequencies for each individual communication channel.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This demands individually tuned resonators, as well as filters to separate out the signals at the receiving end.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The harmonic telegraph achieved this with electromagnetically driven tuned reeds at the transmitting end, which would vibrate similar reeds at the receiving end.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Only the reed with the same resonant frequency as the transmitter would vibrate to any appreciable extent at the receiving end.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Incidentally, the harmonic telegraph directly suggested to Bell the idea of the telephone.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The reeds can be viewed as transducers converting sound to and from an electrical signal.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] It is no great leap from this view of the harmonic telegraph to the idea that speech can be converted to and from an electrical signal.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] By the 1890s, electrical resonance was much more widely understood and had become a normal part of the engineer's toolkit.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] In 1891 Hutin and Leblanc patented an FDM scheme for telephone circuits using resonant circuit filters.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Rival patents were filed in 1892 by Michael Pupin and John Stone Stone with similar ideas, priority eventually being awarded to Pupin.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The basic technical reason for this difficulty is that the frequency response of a simple filter approaches a fall of 6 dB/octave far from the point of resonance.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This means that if telephone channels are squeezed in side by side into the frequency spectrum, there will be crosstalk from adjacent channels in any given channel.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] What is required is a much more sophisticated filter that has a flat frequency response in the required passband like a low-Q resonant circuit, but that rapidly falls in response (much faster than 6 dB/octave) at the transition from passband to stopband like a high-Q resonant circuit.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Obviously, these are contradictory requirements to be met with a single resonant circuit.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The solution to these needs was founded in the theory of transmission lines, and consequently, the necessary filters did not become available until this theory was fully developed.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] At this early stage, the idea of signal bandwidth, and hence the need for filters to match to it, was not fully understood; indeed, it was as late as 1920 before the concept of bandwidth was fully established.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] For early radio, the concepts of Q-factor, selectivity and tuning sufficed.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This was all to change with the developing theory of transmission lines on which image filters are based, as explained in the next section.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] At the turn of the century as telephone lines became available, it became popular to add telegraph onto telephone lines with an earth return phantom circuit.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] An LC filter was required to prevent telegraph clicks being heard on the telephone line.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] From the 1920s onwards, telephone lines, or balanced lines dedicated to the purpose, were used for FDM telegraph at audio frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The first of these systems in the UK was a Siemens and Halske installation between London and Manchester.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Separate pairs were used for the send and receive signals.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The Siemens and GEC systems had six channels of telegraph in each direction; the AT&T system had twelve.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] All of these systems used electronic oscillators to generate a different carrier for each telegraph signal and required a bank of band-pass filters to separate out the multiplexed signal at the receiving end.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The earliest model of the transmission line was probably described by Georg Ohm (1827), who established that resistance in a wire is proportional to its length.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The Ohm model thus included only resistance.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Latimer Clark noted that signals were delayed and elongated along a cable, an undesirable form of distortion now called dispersion but then called retardation, and Michael Faraday (1853) established that this was due to the capacitance present in the transmission line.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Lord Kelvin (1854) found the correct mathematical description needed in his work on early transatlantic cables; he arrived at an equation identical to the conduction of a heat pulse along a metal bar.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This model incorporates only resistance and capacitance, but that is all that was needed in undersea cables dominated by capacitance effects.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Kelvin's model predicts a limit on the telegraph signalling speed of a cable, but Kelvin still did not use the concept of bandwidth; the limit was entirely explained in terms of the dispersion of the telegraph symbols.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The mathematical model of the transmission line reached its fullest development with Oliver Heaviside.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Heaviside (1881) introduced series inductance and shunt conductance into the model, making four distributed elements in all.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This model is now known as the telegrapher's equation and the distributed-element parameters are called the primary line constants.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] From the work of Heaviside (1887) it had become clear that the performance of telegraph lines, and most especially telephone lines, could be improved by the addition of inductance to the line.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] George Campbell at AT&T implemented this idea (1899) by inserting loading coils at intervals along the line.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Campbell found that as well as the desired improvements to the line's characteristics in the passband there was also a definite frequency beyond which signals could not be passed without great attenuation.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This was a result of the loading coils and the line capacitance forming a low-pass filter, an effect that is only apparent on lines incorporating lumped components such as the loading coils.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This naturally led Campbell (1910) to produce a filter with ladder topology.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] A glance at the circuit diagram of this filter is enough to see its relationship to a loaded transmission line.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The cut-off phenomenon is an undesirable side-effect as far as loaded lines are concerned, but for telephone FDM filters it is precisely what is required.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] For this application, Campbell produced band-pass filters to the same ladder topology by replacing the inductors and capacitors with resonators and anti-resonators, respectively.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Both the loaded line and FDM were of great benefit economically to AT&T and this led to fast development of filtering from this point onwards.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The filters designed by Campbell were named wave filters because of their property of passing some waves and strongly rejecting others.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The method by which they were designed was called the image parameter method and filters designed to this method are called image filters.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The image method essentially consists of developing the transmission constants of an infinite chain of identical filter sections and then terminating the desired finite number of filter sections in the image impedance.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This exactly corresponds to the way the properties of a finite length of transmission line are derived from the theoretical properties of an infinite line, the image impedance corresponding to the characteristic impedance of the line.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] From 1920, John Carson, also working for AT&T, began to develop a new way of looking at signals using the operational calculus of Heaviside which in essence is working in the frequency domain.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This gave the AT&T engineers a new insight into the way their filters were working and led Otto Zobel to invent many improved forms.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Carson and Zobel steadily demolished many of the old ideas.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Another advance concerned the nature of noise.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Carson and Zobel (1923) treated noise as a random process with a continuous bandwidth, an idea that was well ahead of its time, and thus limited the amount of noise that it was possible to remove by filtering to that part of the noise spectrum which fell outside the passband.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This too, was not generally accepted at first, notably being opposed by Edwin Armstrong (who ironically, actually succeeded in reducing noise with wide-band FM) and was only finally settled with the work of Harry Nyquist whose thermal noise power formula is well known today.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Several improvements were made to image filters and their theory of operation by Otto Zobel.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Zobel coined the term constant k filter (or k-type filter) to distinguish Campbell's filter from later types, notably Zobel's m-derived filter (or m-type filter).
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The particular problems Zobel was trying to address with these new forms were impedance matching into the end terminations and improved steepness of roll-off.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] These were achieved at the cost of an increase in filter circuit complexity.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] A more systematic method of producing image filters was introduced by Hendrik Bode (1930), and further developed by several other investigators, including Piloty (1937–1939) and Wilhelm Cauer (1934–1937).
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Rather than enumerate the behaviour (transfer function, attenuation function, delay function and so on) of a specific circuit, a requirement for the image impedance itself was developed.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The behaviour of the filter can be entirely defined in terms of the positions in the complex plane of these pairs of poles and zeroes.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Any circuit that has the requisite poles and zeroes will also have the requisite response.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Cauer pursued two related questions arising from this technique: what specification of poles and zeroes are realisable as passive filters, and what realisations are equivalent to each other.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The results of this work led Cauer to develop a new approach, now called network synthesis.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This poles and zeroes view of filter design was particularly useful where a bank of filters, each operating at different frequencies, are all connected across the same transmission line.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The earlier approach was unable to deal properly with this situation, but the poles and zeroes approach could embrace it by specifying a constant impedance for the combined filter.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This problem was originally related to FDM telephony, but frequently now arises in loudspeaker crossover filters.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The essence of network synthesis is to start with a required filter response and produce a network that delivers that response, or approximates it within a specified boundary.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This is the inverse of network analysis, which starts with a given network and, by applying the various electric circuit theorems, predicts the response of the network.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The term was first used with this meaning in the doctoral thesis of Yuk-Wing Lee (1930) and apparently arose out of a conversation with Vannevar Bush.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The advantage of network synthesis over previous methods is that it provides a solution which precisely meets the design specification.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This is not the case with image filters; a degree of experience is required in their design since the image filter only meets the design specification in the unrealistic case of being terminated in its own image impedance.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Network synthesis, on the other hand, takes care of the termination impedances simply by incorporating them into the network being designed.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The development of network analysis needed to take place before network synthesis was possible.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The theorems of Gustav Kirchhoff and others and the ideas of Charles Steinmetz (phasors) and Arthur Kennelly (complex impedance) laid the groundwork.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The concept of a port also played a part in the development of the theory, and proved to be a more useful idea than network terminals.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The first milestone on the way to network synthesis was an important paper by Ronald M.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Foster (1924), *A Reactance Theorem*, in which Foster introduces the idea of a driving point impedance, that is, the impedance that is connected to the generator.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The expression for this impedance determines the response of the filter and vice versa, and a realisation of the filter can be obtained by expansion of this expression.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] It is not possible to realise any arbitrary impedance expression as a network.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Foster's reactance theorem stipulates necessary and sufficient conditions for realisability: that the reactance must be algebraically increasing with frequency and the poles and zeroes must alternate.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Wilhelm Cauer expanded on the work of Foster (1926) and was the first to talk of realisation of a one-port impedance with a prescribed frequency function.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Foster's work considered only reactances (i.e., only LC-kind circuits).
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Cauer generalised this to any 2-element kind one-port network, finding there was an isomorphism between them.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] He also found ladder realisations of the network using Thomas Stieltjes' continued fraction expansion.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Designers tend to avoid the complication of mutual inductances and transformers where possible, although transformer-coupled double-tuned amplifiers are a common way of widening bandwidth without sacrificing selectivity.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Image filters continued to be used by designers long after the superior network synthesis techniques were available.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Part of the reason for this may have been simply inertia, but it was largely due to the greater computation required for network synthesis filters, often needing a mathematical iterative process.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Image filters, in their simplest form, consist of a chain of repeated, identical sections.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The design can be improved simply by adding more sections and the computation required to produce the initial section is on the level of "back of an envelope" designing.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] In the case of network synthesis filters, on the other hand, the filter is designed as a whole, single entity, and to add more sections (i.e., increase the order) the designer would have no option but to go back to the beginning and start over.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The advantages of synthesised designs are real, but they are not overwhelming compared to what a skilled image designer could achieve, and in many cases it was more cost effective to dispense with time-consuming calculations.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This is simply not an issue with the modern availability of computing power, but in the 1950s it was non-existent, in the 1960s and 1970s available only at cost, and not finally becoming widely available to all designers until the 1980s with the advent of the desktop personal computer.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Image filters continued to be designed up to that point and many remained in service into the 21st century.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The computational difficulty of the network synthesis method was addressed by tabulating the component values of a prototype filter and then scaling the frequency impedance and transforming the bandform to those actually required.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This kind of approach, or similar, was already in use with image filters, for instance by Zobel, but the concept of a "reference filter" is due to Sidney Darlington.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Darlington (1939), was also the first to tabulate values for network synthesis prototype filters; nevertheless, it had to wait until the 1950s before the Cauer-Darlington elliptic filter first came into use.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Once computational power was readily available, it became possible to easily design filters to minimise any arbitrary parameter, for example, time delay or tolerance to component variation.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The difficulties of the image method were firmly put in the past, and even the need for prototypes became largely superfluous.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Furthermore, the advent of active filters eased the computation difficulty because sections could be isolated and iterative processes were not then generally necessary.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Realisability (that is, which functions are realisable as real impedance networks) and equivalence (which networks equivalently have the same function) are two important questions in network synthesis.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] where [**Z**],[**R**],[**L**] and [**D**] are the *n*x*n* matrices of, respectively, impedance, resistance, inductance and elastance of an *n*-mesh network and *s* is the complex frequency operator $\scriptstyle s=\sigma +i\omega$ .
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Here [**R**],[**L**] and [**D**] have associated energies corresponding to the kinetic, potential and dissipative heat energies, respectively, in a mechanical system, and the already known results from mechanics could be applied here.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] where *a11* is the complement of the element *A11* to which the one-port is to be connected.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] From stability theory Cauer found that [**R**], [**L**] and [**D**] must all be positive-definite matrices for *Z*p(*s*) to be realisable if ideal transformers are not excluded.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Realisability is only otherwise restricted by practical limitations on topology.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This work is also partly due to Otto Brune (1931), who worked with Cauer in the US prior to Cauer returning to Germany.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] A well-known condition for realisability of a one-port rational impedance due to Cauer (1929) is that it must be a function of *s* that is analytic in the right halfplane (σ>0), have a positive real part in the right halfplane and take on real values on the real axis.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This follows from the Poisson integral representation of these functions.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Brune coined the term positive-real for this class of function and proved that it was a necessary and sufficient condition (Cauer had only proved it to be necessary) and they extended the work to LC multiports.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] A theorem due to Sidney Darlington states that any positive-real function *Z*(*s*) can be realised as a lossless two-port terminated in a positive resistor R.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] No resistors within the network are necessary to realise the specified response.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] is invariant in *Z*p(*s*), that is, all the transformed networks are equivalent to the original.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The approximation problem in network synthesis is to find functions that will produce realisable networks approximating to a prescribed function of frequency within limits arbitrarily set.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The approximation problem is an important issue since the ideal function of frequency required will commonly be unachievable with rational networks.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] For instance, the ideal prescribed function is often taken to be the unachievable lossless transmission in the passband, infinite attenuation in the stopband and a vertical transition between the two.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] However, the ideal function can be approximated with a rational function, becoming ever closer to the ideal the higher the order of the polynomial.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The first to address this problem was Stephen Butterworth (1930) using his Butterworth polynomials.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Independently, Cauer (1931) used Chebyshev polynomials, initially applied to image filters, and not to the now well-known ladder realisation of this filter.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Butterworth filters are an important class of filters due to Stephen Butterworth (1930) which are now recognised as being a special case of Cauer's elliptic filters.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This gives Butterworth the credit for being both the first to deviate from image parameter theory and the first to design active filters.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] It was later shown that Butterworth filters could be implemented in ladder topology without the need for amplifiers.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Possibly the first to do so was William Bennett (1932) in a patent which presents formulae for component values identical to the modern ones.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Bennett, at this stage, though, is still discussing the design as an artificial transmission line and so is adopting an image parameter approach despite having produced what would now be considered a network synthesis design.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] He also does not appear to be aware of the work of Butterworth or the connection between them.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Versions of this theory are due to Sidney Darlington, Wilhelm Cauer, and others, all working more or less independently, and are often taken as synonymous with network synthesis.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Butterworth's filter implementation is, in those terms, an insertion-loss filter, but it is a relatively trivial one mathematically since the active amplifiers used by Butterworth ensured that each stage individually worked into a resistive load.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Butterworth's filter becomes a non-trivial example when it is implemented entirely with passive components.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] An even earlier filter that influenced the insertion-loss method was Norton's dual-band filter, where the inputs of two filters are connected in parallel and designed so that the combined input presents a constant resistance.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Norton's design method, together with Cauer's canonical LC networks and Darlington's theorem that only LC components were required in the body of the filter, resulted in the insertion-loss method.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] However, ladder topology proved to be more practical than Cauer's canonical forms.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Darlington's insertion-loss method is a generalisation of the procedure used by Norton.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] In Norton's filter, it can be shown that each filter is equivalent to a separate filter unterminated at the common end.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Darlington's method applies to the more straightforward and general case of a 2-port LC network terminated at both ends.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] 5. expand the driving point impedance into an LC (usually ladder) network.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Darlington additionally used a transformation found by Hendrik Bode that predicted the response of a filter using non-ideal components but all with the same *Q*.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Darlington used this transformation in reverse to produce filters with a prescribed insertion-loss with non-ideal components.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Such filters have the ideal insertion-loss response plus a flat attenuation across all frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Elliptic filters are filters produced by the insertion-loss method, which use elliptic rational functions in their transfer function as an approximation to the ideal filter response, and the result is called a Chebyshev approximation.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This is the same Chebyshev approximation technique used by Cauer on image filters, but follows the Darlington insertion-loss design method and uses slightly different elliptic functions.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Cauer had some contact with Darlington and Bell Labs before WWII (for a time, he worked in the US), but during the war, they worked independently, in some cases making the same discoveries.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Cauer had disclosed the Chebyshev approximation to Bell Labs but had not left them with the proof.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Sergei Schelkunoff provided this and a generalisation to all equal ripple problems.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] where *F* is either an even (resulting in an antimetric filter) or an odd (resulting in a symmetric filter) function of frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Zeros of *F* correspond to zero loss, and the poles of *F* correspond to transmission zeroes.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] *J* sets the passband ripple height and the stopband loss, and these two design requirements can be interchanged.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The zeroes and poles of *F* and *J* can be set arbitrarily.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] A Chebyshev response simultaneously in the passband and stopband is possible, such as Cauer's equal ripple elliptic filter.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Darlington relates that he found in the New York City library Carl Jacobi's original paper on elliptic functions, published in Latin in 1829.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] In this paper, Darlington was surprised to find foldout tables of the exact elliptic function transformations needed for Chebyshev approximations of both Cauer's image parameter and Darlington's insertion-loss filters.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Darlington considers the topology of coupled tuned circuits to involve a separate approximation technique to the insertion-loss method, but also producing nominally flat passbands and high attenuation stopbands.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The most common topology for these is shunt anti-resonators coupled by series capacitors, less commonly, by inductors, or in the case of a two-section filter, by mutual inductance.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] These are most useful where the design requirement is not too stringent, that is, moderate bandwidth, roll-off and passband ripple.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Edward Norton, around 1930, designed a mechanical filter for use on phonograph recorders and players.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Norton designed the filter in the electrical domain and then used the correspondence of mechanical quantities to electrical quantities to realise the filter using mechanical components.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Mass corresponds to inductance, stiffness to elastance and damping to resistance.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The filter was designed to have a maximally flat frequency response.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] In modern designs, it is common to use quartz crystal filters, especially for narrowband filtering applications.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The signal exists as a mechanical acoustic wave while it is in the crystal and is converted by transducers between the electrical and mechanical domains at the terminals of the crystal.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Distributed-element filters are composed of lengths of transmission line that are at least a significant fraction of a wavelength long.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The earliest non-electrical filters were all of this type.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] William Herschel (1738–1822), for instance, constructed an apparatus with two tubes of different lengths which attenuated some frequencies but not others.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Joseph-Louis Lagrange (1736–1813) studied waves on a string periodically loaded with weights.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The device was never studied or used as a filter by either Lagrange or later investigators such as Charles Godfrey.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] However, Campbell used Godfrey's results by analogy to calculate the number of loading coils needed on his loaded lines, the device that led to his electrical filter development.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Lagrange, Godfrey, and Campbell all made simplifying assumptions in their calculations that ignored the distributed nature of their apparatus.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Consequently, their models did not show the multiple passbands that are a characteristic of all distributed-element filters.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The first electrical filters that were truly designed by distributed-element principles are due to Warren P.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Transversal filters are not usually associated with passive implementations, but the concept can be found in a Wiener and Lee patent from 1935, which describes a filter consisting of a cascade of all-pass sections.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The outputs of the various sections are summed in the proportions needed to result in the required frequency function.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This works by the principle that certain frequencies will be in, or close to antiphase, at different sections and will tend to cancel when added.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] These are the frequencies rejected by the filter and can produce filters with very sharp cut-offs.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] This approach did not find any immediate applications and is not common in passive filters.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] However, the principle finds many applications as an active delay line implementation for wide band discrete-time filter applications such as television, radar and high-speed data transmission.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The purpose of matched filters is to maximise the signal-to-noise ratio (S/N) at the expense of pulse shape.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Pulse shape, unlike many other applications, is unimportant in radar, while S/N is the primary limitation on performance.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] The filters were introduced during WWII (described 1943) by Dwight North and are often eponymously referred to as "North filters".
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Control systems have a need for smoothing filters in their feedback loops with criteria to maximise the speed of movement of a mechanical system to the prescribed mark and at the same time minimise overshoot and noise-induced motions.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] A key problem here is the extraction of Gaussian signals from a noisy background.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] An early paper on this was published during WWII by Norbert Wiener with the specific application to anti-aircraft fire control analogue computers.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Rudy Kalman (Kalman filter) later reformulated this in terms of state-space smoothing and prediction, where it is known as the linear-quadratic-Gaussian control problem.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Kalman started an interest in state-space solutions, but according to Darlington, this approach can also be found in the work of Heaviside and earlier.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] LC filters at low frequencies become awkward; the components, especially the inductors, become expensive, bulky, heavy, and non-ideal.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Practical 1 H inductors require many turns on a high-permeability core; that material will have high losses and stability issues (e.g., a large temperature coefficient).
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] For applications such as a mains filter, the awkwardness must be tolerated.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] For low-level, low-frequency applications, RC filters are possible, but they cannot implement filters with complex poles or zeros.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] If the application can use power, then amplifiers can be used to make RC active filters that can have complex poles and zeros.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] In the 1950s, Sallen–Key active RC filters were made with vacuum tube amplifiers; these filters replaced the bulky inductors with bulky and hot vacuum tubes.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Transistors offered more power-efficient active filter designs.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Later, inexpensive operational amplifiers enabled other active RC filter design topologies.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Although active filter designs were commonplace at low frequencies, they were impractical at high frequencies where the amplifiers were not ideal; LC (and transmission line) filters were still used at radio frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Gradually, the low-frequency active RC filter was supplanted by the switched-capacitor filter that operated in the discrete time domain rather than the continuous time domain.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] All of these filter technologies require precision components for high-performance filtering, and that often requires that the filters be tuned.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Adjustable components are expensive, and the labor to do the tuning can be significant.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Tuning the poles and zeros of a 7th-order elliptic filter is not a simple exercise.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Integrated circuits have made digital computation inexpensive, so now low-frequency filtering is done with digital signal processors.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Such digital filters have no problem implementing ultra-precise (and stable) values, so no tuning or adjustment is required.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Digital filters also don't have to worry about stray coupling paths and shielding the individual filter sections from one another.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] One downside is the digital signal processing may consume much more power than an equivalent LC filter.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Inexpensive digital technology has largely supplanted analogue implementations of filters.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] However, there is still an occasional place for them in the simpler applications, such as coupling, where sophisticated functions of frequency are not needed.
[src:electronic-filter/analog-filter] Passive filters are still the technology of choice at microwave frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] Typically, a datasheet is created by the manufacturer and begins with an introductory page describing the rest of the document, followed by listings of specific characteristics, with further information on the connectivity of the devices.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] In cases where there is relevant source code to include, it is usually attached near the end of the document or separated into another file.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] Datasheets are created, stored, and distributed via product information management or product data management systems.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] Depending on the specific purpose, a datasheet may offer an average value, a typical value, a typical range, engineering tolerances, or a nominal value.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] The type and source of data are usually stated on the datasheet.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] A datasheet is usually used for commercial or technical communication to describe the characteristics of an item or product.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] It can be published by the manufacturer to help people choose products or to help use the products.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] By contrast, a technical specification is an explicit set of requirements to be satisfied by a material, product, or service.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] The ideal datasheet specifies characteristics in a formal structure, according to a strict taxonomy, that allows the information to be processed by a machine.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] Such machine readable descriptions can facilitate information retrieval, display, design, testing, interfacing, verification, system discovery, and e-commerce.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] Examples include Open Icecat data-sheets, transducer electronic data sheets for describing sensor characteristics, and electronic device descriptions in CANopen or descriptions in markup languages, such as SensorML.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] A product data sheet (PDS), like any datasheet, has a different data model per category.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] In Open Icecat, the global open catalog or open content project in which hundreds of manufacturers and thousands of e-commerce sellers participate, the data models of tens of thousands of taxonomy classes are defined, and millions of free PDSs can be found conforming these data-sheet data models.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] A material safety data sheet (MSDS), safety data sheet (SDS), or product safety data sheet (PSDS) is an important component of product stewardship and occupational safety and health.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] These are required by agencies such as OSHA in its Hazard Communication Standard, 29 C.F.R.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] It provides workers with ways to allow them to work in a safe manner and gives them physical data (melting point, boiling point, flash point, etc.), toxicity, health effects, first aid, reactivity, storage, disposal, protective equipment, and spill-handling procedures.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] The MSDSs differ from country to country, as different countries have different regulations.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] In some jurisdictions, it is compulsory for the SDS to state the chemical's risks, safety, and effect on the environment.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] The SDSs are a commonly used classification for logging information on chemicals, chemical compounds, and chemical mixtures.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] The SDSs often include the safe use of the chemical and the hazardous nature of the chemical.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] Anytime chemicals are used these datasheets will be found.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] There is a need to have an internationally recognized symbol when describing hazardous substances.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] Labels can include hazard symbols such as the European Union standard black diagonal cross on an orange background, used to denote a harmful substance.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] The purpose of an SDS is not so that the general public will have a knowledge of how to read and understand it, but more so that it can be used in an occupational setting to allow workers to be able to work with it.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] Datasheets and pages are available for specific properties of chemicals in chemical elements data references: example, melting points of the elements (data page).
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] Specific materials have technical data in individual sheets such as ethanol: this includes subjects such as structure and properties, thermodynamic properties, spectral data, vapor pressure, etc.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] Other chemical datasheets are available from individual producers of chemicals, often on their web pages.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] Datasheets for automobiles may be described under several names such as features, specs, engineering data, technical summary, etc.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] They help communicate the technical information about a car to potential buyers and are useful for comparisons with similar cars.
[src:electronic-filter/application-note] They might include: critical inside and outside dimensions, weight, fuel efficiency, engine and drive train, towing capability, safety features and options, warranty, etc.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] An **atomic clock** is a clock that measures time by monitoring the resonant frequency of atoms.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] It is based on the fact that atoms have quantised energy levels, and transitions between such levels are driven by very specific frequencies of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This definition underpins the system of TAI, which is maintained by an ensemble of atomic clocks around the world.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The system of UTC — the basis of civil time — implements leap seconds to allow clock time to stay within one second of Earth's rotation.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The accurate time-keeping capabilities of atomic clocks are also used for navigation by satellite networks such as the EU’s Galileo Programme and the United States’ GPS.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The timing accuracy of the atomic clocks matters because even a timing error of 1 nanosecond (10−9 s) corresponds to a positional error of roughly 30 cm when multiplied by the speed of light.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The main variety of atomic clock in use today employs caesium atoms (or ions) cooled to near absolute zero.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] For example, the United States’ primary standard, the NIST caesium fountain clock named NIST-F2, operates with a relative uncertainty around 10−16.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In July 2025, researchers at the National Institute of Standards and Technology in the United States reported a record-setting optical atomic clock based on a trapped aluminium ion.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This "quantum logic" clock achieves a systematic uncertainty corresponding to around 19 decimal places of accuracy, representing a 41% improvement over the previous record and being 2.6 times more stable than any other ion clock.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The rapid improvement in optical atomic clock performance has prompted the global time-and-frequency community to prepare for a possible redefinition of the SI second.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In June 2025, a coordinated international comparison of optical clocks across six countries was reported — marking a major step towards establishing a global optical-time standard.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Optical atomic clocks are enabling new applications: ultra-precise time- and-frequency dissemination, improved global navigation satellite systems, relativistic geodesy (measuring differences in gravitational potential via clock rates), and tests of fundamental constants and general relativity.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] During the 1930s, the American physicist Isidor Isaac Rabi built equipment for atomic beam magnetic resonance frequency clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The accuracy of mechanical, electromechanical and quartz clocks is reduced by temperature fluctuations.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This led to the idea of measuring the frequency of an atom's vibrations to keep time more accurately, as proposed by James Clerk Maxwell, Lord Kelvin, and Isidor Rabi.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A prototype measuring phase transitions of the ammonia molecule was developed in 1949.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The first practical atomic clock using caesium atoms was built at the National Physical Laboratory in the United Kingdom in 1955 by Louis Essen in collaboration with Jack Parry.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In 1949, Alfred Kastler and Jean Brossel developed a technique called optical pumping for electron energy level transitions in atoms using light.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This technique is useful for creating much stronger magnetic resonance and microwave absorption signals.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Unfortunately, this caused a side effect with a light shift of the resonant frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Claude Cohen-Tannoudji and others managed to reduce the light shifts to acceptable levels.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Ramsey developed a method, now commonly known as Ramsey interferometry, for higher frequencies and narrower resonances in the oscillating fields.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Kolsky, Phipps, Ramsey, and Silsbee used this technique for molecular beam spectroscopy in 1950.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] During the 1950s, the National Radio Company sold more than 50 units of the first atomic clock, the Atomichron.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In 1964, engineers at Hewlett-Packard released the 5060 rack-mounted model of caesium clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In 1968, the SI defined the duration of the second to be 9192631770 vibrations of the unperturbed ground-state hyperfine transition frequency of the caesium-133 atom.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Prior to that it was defined by there being 31556925.9747 seconds in the tropical year 1900.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In 1997, the International Committee for Weights and Measures (CIPM) added that the preceding definition refers to a caesium atom at rest at a temperature of absolute zero.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Following the 2019 revision of the SI, the definition of every base unit except the mole and almost every derived unit relies on the definition of the second.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Timekeeping researchers seek an even more stable atomic reference for the second, with a plan to find a more precise definition of the second as atomic clocks improve based on optical clocks or the Rydberg constant around 2030.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Technological developments such as lasers and optical frequency combs in the 1990s led to increasing accuracy of atomic clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Lasers enable the possibility of optical-range control over atomic states transitions, which has a much higher frequency than that of microwaves; while optical frequency comb measures highly accurately such high frequency oscillation in light.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The first advance beyond the precision of caesium clocks occurred at NIST in 2010 with the demonstration of a "quantum logic" optical clock that used aluminum ions to achieve a precision of 10−17.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Optical clocks are a very active area of research in the field of metrology as scientists work to develop clocks based on elements ytterbium, mercury, aluminum, and strontium.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Scientists at JILA demonstrated a strontium clock with a frequency precision of 10−18 in 2015.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Scientists at NIST developed a quantum logic clock that measured a single aluminum ion in 2019 with a frequency uncertainty of 9.4×10−19.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] At JILA in September 2021, scientists demonstrated an optical strontium clock with a differential frequency precision of 7.6×10−21 between atomic ensembles separated by 1 mm.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The second is expected to be redefined when the field of optical clocks matures, sometime around the year 2030 or 2034.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In order for this to occur, optical clocks must be consistently capable of measuring frequency with accuracy at or better than 2×10−18.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In addition, methods for reliably comparing different optical clocks around the world in national metrology labs must be demonstrated, and the comparison must show relative clock frequency accuracies at or better than 5×10−18.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Reducing the size and power consumption of optical clocks is necessary to enable their use in geodesy and GPS navigation.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In August 2004, NIST scientists demonstrated a chip-scale atomic clock that was 100 times smaller than an ordinary atomic clock and had a much smaller power consumption of 125 mW.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The atomic clock was about the size of a grain of rice with a frequency of about 9 GHz.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This technology became available commercially in 2011.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] An atomic clock is based on a system of atoms which may be in one of two possible energy states.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A group of atoms is prepared in a lower energy state, and then subjected to microwave radiation.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] If the radiation is of the correct frequency, a number of atoms will transition to the higher energy state.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The closer the frequency is to the inherent oscillation frequency of the atoms, the more atoms will switch states.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Such correlation allows very accurate tuning of the frequency of the microwave radiation.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Once the microwave radiation is adjusted to a known frequency where the maximum number of atoms switch states, the atom and thus, its associated transition frequency, can be used as a timekeeping oscillator to measure elapsed time.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] All timekeeping devices use oscillatory phenomena to accurately measure time, whether it is the rotation of the Earth for a sundial, the swinging of a pendulum in a grandfather clock, the vibrations of springs and gears in a watch, or voltage changes in a quartz crystal watch.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] However all of these are easily affected by temperature changes and are not very accurate.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The most accurate clocks use atomic vibrations to keep track of time.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Clock transition states in atoms are insensitive to temperature and other environmental factors and the oscillation frequency is much higher than any of the other clocks (in microwave frequency regime and higher).
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] One of the most important factors in a clock's performance is the atomic line quality factor, *Q*, which is defined as the ratio of the absolute frequency $\nu _{0}$ of the resonance to the linewidth of the resonance itself $\Delta \nu$ .
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic resonance has a much higher *Q* than mechanical devices.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks can also be isolated from environmental effects to a much higher degree.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks have the benefit that atoms are universal, which means that the oscillation frequency is also universal.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This is different from quartz and mechanical time measurement devices that do not have a universal frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A clock's quality can be specified by two parameters: accuracy and stability.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Accuracy is a measurement of the degree to which the clock's ticking rate can be counted on to match some absolute standard such as the inherent hyperfine frequency of an isolated atom or ion.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Stability describes how the clock performs when averaged over time to reduce the impact of noise and other short-term fluctuations (see precision).
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The instability of an atomic clock is specified by its Allan deviation $\sigma _{y}(\tau )$ .
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] where $\Delta \nu$ is the spectroscopic linewidth of the clock system, N is the number of atoms or ions used in a single measurement, $T_{\text{c}}$ is the time required for one cycle, and $\tau$ is the averaging period.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This means instability is smaller when the linewidth $\Delta \nu$ is smaller and when ${\sqrt {N}}$ (the signal to noise ratio) is larger.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The stability improves as the time $\tau$ over which the measurements are averaged increases from seconds to hours to days.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The stability is most heavily affected by the oscillator frequency $\nu _{0}$ .
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This is why optical clocks such as strontium clocks (429 terahertz) are much more stable than caesium clocks (9.19 GHz).
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Modern clocks such as atomic fountains or optical lattices that use sequential interrogation are found to generate a type of noise that mimics and adds to the instability inherent in atom or ion counting.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This effect is called the Dick effect and is typically the primary stability limitation for the newer atomic clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] It is an aliasing effect; high frequency noise components in the local oscillator ("LO") are heterodyned to near zero frequency by harmonics of the repeating variation in feedback sensitivity to the LO frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The effect places new and stringent requirements on the LO, which must now have low phase noise in addition to high stability, thereby increasing the cost and complexity of the system.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This expression shows the same dependence on $T_{c}/{\tau }$ as does $\sigma _{y,\,{\rm {atoms}}}(\tau )$ , and, for many of the newer clocks, is significantly larger.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Analysis of the effect and its consequence as applied to optical standards has been treated in a major review (Ludlow, et al., 2015) that lamented on "the pernicious influence of the Dick effect", and in several other papers.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The core of atomic clocks contain a microwave cavity containing a gas.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In a hydrogen maser clock, the gas emits microwaves (*masering*) on a hyperfine transition.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] As the field in the cavity oscillates, the cavity is tuned for maximum microwave amplitude.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The adjustment tries to correct for unwanted side-effects, such as frequencies from other electron transitions, temperature changes, and the spreading in frequencies caused by the vibration of molecules, including Doppler broadening.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Many of the newer clocks, including microwave clocks such as trapped-ion or fountain clocks, and optical clocks such as lattice clocks, use a sequential interrogation protocol rather than the frequency-modulation interrogation.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] An advantage of sequential interrogation is that it can accommodate much higher Qs, with ringing times of seconds rather than milliseconds.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These clocks also typically have a *dead time*, during which the atom or ion collections are analyzed, renewed and driven into a proper quantum state, after which they are interrogated with a signal from a *local oscillator* (LO) for a time of perhaps a second or so.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Analysis of the final state of the atoms is then used to generate a correction signal to keep the LO frequency locked to that of the atoms or ions.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The accuracy of atomic clocks has improved continuously since the first prototype in the 1950s.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The first generation of atomic clocks were based on measuring caesium, rubidium, and hydrogen atoms.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In a time period from 1959 to 1998, NIST developed a series of seven caesium-133 microwave clocks named NBS-1 to NBS-6 and NIST-7 after the agency changed its name from the National Bureau of Standards to the National Institute of Standards and Technology.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The first clock had an accuracy of 10−11, and the last clock had an accuracy of 10−15.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The clocks were the first to use a caesium fountain, which was introduced by Jerrod Zacharias, and laser cooling of atoms, which was demonstrated by Dave Wineland and his colleagues in 1978.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The next step in atomic clock advances involves going from accuracies of 10−15 to accuracies of 10−18 and even 10−19.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The goal is to redefine the second when clocks become so accurate that they will not lose or gain more than a second in the age of the universe.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] To do so, scientists must demonstrate the accuracy of clocks that use strontium and ytterbium and optical lattice technology.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Such clocks are also called optical clocks where the energy level transitions used are in the optical regime (giving rise to even higher oscillation frequency), which thus, have much higher accuracy as compared to traditional atomic clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The goal of an atomic clock with 10−16 accuracy was first reached at the United Kingdom's National Physical Laboratory's NPL-CsF2 caesium fountain clock and the United States' NIST-F2.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The increase in precision from NIST-F1 to NIST-F2 is due to liquid nitrogen cooling of the microwave interaction region; the largest source of uncertainty in NIST-F1 is the effect of black-body radiation from the warm chamber walls.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The performance of primary and secondary frequency standards contributing to International Atomic Time (TAI) is evaluated.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The evaluation reports of individual (mainly primary) clocks are published online by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM).
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] They do this by designing and building frequency standards that produce electric oscillations at a frequency whose relationship to the transition frequency of caesium 133 is known, in order to achieve a very low uncertainty.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These primary frequency standards estimate and correct various frequency shifts, including relativistic Doppler shifts linked to atomic motion, the thermal radiation of the environment (blackbody shift) and several other factors.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The best primary standards currently produce the SI second with an accuracy approaching an uncertainty of one part in 1016.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] At this level of accuracy, the differences in the gravitational field in the device cannot be ignored.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The standard is then considered in the framework of general relativity to provide a proper time at a specific point.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic time standards such as International Atomic Time (TAI) and Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) are disseminated to the public through satellite navigation systems, radio time signals, and network-based time services.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These tools can be used to observe clock deviation and synchronization discrepancies in end-user devices.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM) provides a list of frequencies that serve as secondary representations of the second.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This list contains the frequency values and respective standard uncertainties for the rubidium microwave transition and other optical transitions, including neutral atoms and single trapped ions.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These secondary frequency standards can be as accurate as one part in 1018; however, the uncertainties in the list are one part in 1014–1016.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This is because the uncertainty in the central caesium standard against which the secondary standards are calibrated is one part in 1014–1016.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Primary frequency standards can be used to calibrate the frequency of other clocks used in national laboratories.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These are usually commercial caesium clocks having very good long-term frequency stability, maintaining a frequency with a stability better than 1 part in 1014 over a few months.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The uncertainty of the primary standard frequencies is around one part in 1013.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Hydrogen masers, which rely on the 1.4 GHz hyperfine transition in atomic hydrogen, are also used in time metrology laboratories.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Masers outperform any commercial caesium clock in terms of short-term frequency stability.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In the past, these instruments have been used in all applications that require a steady reference across time periods of less than one day (frequency stability of about 1 part in ten for averaging times of a few hours).
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Because some active hydrogen masers have a modest but predictable frequency drift with time, they have become an important part of the BIPM's ensemble of commercial clocks that implement International Atomic Time.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The time readings of clocks operated in metrology labs operating with the BIPM need to be known very accurately.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Some operations require synchronization of atomic clocks separated by great distances over thousands of kilometers.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Global Navigational Satellite Systems (GNSS) provide a satisfactory solution to the problem of time transfer.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks are used to broadcast time signals in the United States Global Positioning System (GPS), the Russian Federation's Global Navigation Satellite System (GLONASS), the European Union's Galileo system and China's BeiDou system.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The signal received from one satellite in a metrology laboratory equipped with a receiver with an accurately known position allows the time difference between the local time scale and the GNSS system time to be determined with an uncertainty of a few nanoseconds when averaged over 15 minutes.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Receivers allow the simultaneous reception of signals from several satellites, and make use of signals transmitted on two frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] As more satellites are launched and start operations, time measurements will become more accurate.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These methods of time comparison must make corrections for the effects of special relativity and general relativity of a few nanoseconds.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These four European labs are developing and host a variety of experimental optical clocks that harness different elements in different experimental set-ups and want to compare their optical clocks against each other and check whether they agree.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] National laboratories usually operate a range of clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These are operated independently of one another and their measurements are sometimes combined to generate a scale that is more stable and more accurate than that of any individual contributing clock.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This scale allows for time comparisons between different clocks in the laboratory.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These atomic time scales are generally referred to as TA(k) for laboratory k.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) is the result of comparing clocks in national laboratories around the world to International Atomic Time (TAI), then adding leap seconds as necessary.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] TAI is a weighted average of around 450 clocks in some 80 time institutions.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The relative stability of TAI is around one part in 1016.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Before TAI is published, the frequency of the result is compared with the SI second at various primary and secondary frequency standards.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This requires relativistic corrections to be applied to the location of the primary standard which depend on the distance between the equal gravity potential and the rotating geoid of Earth.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The values of the rotating geoid and the TAI change slightly each month and are available in the BIPM Circular T publication.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The TAI time-scale is deferred by a few weeks as the average of atomic clocks around the world is calculated.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] TAI is not distributed in everyday timekeeping.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Instead, an integer number of leap seconds are added or subtracted to correct for the Earth's rotation, producing UTC.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The number of leap seconds is changed so that mean solar noon at the prime meridian (Greenwich) does not deviate from UTC noon by more than 0.9 seconds.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] National metrology institutions maintain an approximation of UTC referred to as UTC(k) for laboratory k.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] UTC(k) is distributed by the BIPM's Consultative Committee for Time and Frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The offset UTC-UTC(k) is calculated every 5 days, the results are published monthly.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks record UTC(k) to no more than 100 nanoseconds.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In some countries, UTC(k) is the legal time that is distributed by radio, television, telephone, Internet, fiber-optic cables, time signal transmitters, and speaking clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In addition, GNSS provides time information accurate to a few tens of nanoseconds or better.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In a next phase, these labs strive to transmit comparison signals in the visible spectrum through fibre-optic cables.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This will allow their experimental optical clocks to be compared with an accuracy similar to the expected accuracies of the optical clocks themselves.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Some of these labs have already established fibre-optic links, and tests have begun on sections between Paris and Teddington, and Paris and Braunschweig.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Fibre-optic links between experimental optical clocks also exist between the American NIST lab and its partner lab JILA, both in Boulder, Colorado but these span much shorter distances than the European network and are between just two labs.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] According to Fritz Riehle, a physicist at PTB, "Europe is in a unique position as it has a high density of the best clocks in the world".
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The fractional uncertainty of the whole link was assessed to be 2.5×10−19, making comparisons of even more accurate clocks possible.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In 2021, NIST compared transmission of signals from a series of experimental atomic clocks located about 1.5 km (1 mi) apart at the NIST lab, its partner lab JILA, and the University of Colorado all in Boulder, Colorado over air and fiber optic cable to a precision of 8×10−18.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The SI second is defined as a certain number of unperturbed ground-state hyperfine transitions of the caesium-133 atom.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Caesium standards are therefore regarded as primary time and frequency standards.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Caesium clocks include the NIST-F1 clock, developed in 1999, and the NIST-F2 clock, developed in 2013.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Caesium has several properties that make it a good choice for an atomic clock.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Whereas a hydrogen atom moves at 1,600 m/s at room temperature and a nitrogen atom moves at 510 m/s, a caesium atom moves at a much slower speed of 130 m/s due to its greater mass.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The hyperfine frequency of caesium (~9.19 GHz) is also higher than other elements such as rubidium (~6.8 GHz) and hydrogen (~1.4 GHz).
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The high frequency of caesium allows for more accurate measurements.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Caesium reference tubes suitable for national standards currently last about seven years and cost about US$35,000.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Primary frequency and time standards like the United States Time Standard atomic clocks, NIST-F1 and NIST-F2, use far higher power.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In a caesium beam frequency reference, timing signals are derived from a high stability voltage-controlled quartz crystal oscillator (VCXO) that is tunable over a narrow range.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The output frequency of the VCXO (typically 5 MHz) is multiplied by a frequency synthesizer to obtain microwaves at the frequency of the caesium atomic hyperfine transition (about 9192.6317 MHz).
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The output of the frequency synthesizer is amplified and applied to a chamber containing caesium gas which absorbs the microwaves.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The output current of the caesium chamber increases as absorption increases.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The remainder of the circuitry simply adjusts the running frequency of the VCXO to maximize the output current of the caesium chamber which keeps the oscillator tuned to the resonance frequency of the hyperfine transition.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The BIPM defines the unperturbed ground-state hyperfine transition frequency of the rubidium-87 atom; 6,834,682,610.9043126 Hz; in terms of the caesium standard frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks based on rubidium standards are therefore regarded as secondary representations of the second.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The advantages of rubidium atomic clocks are their low cost, small size (commercial standards are as small as 1.7×105 mm3) and short-term stability.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] They are used in many commercial, portable and aerospace applications.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Modern rubidium standard tubes last more than ten years, and can cost as little as US$50.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Some commercial applications use a rubidium standard periodically corrected by a global positioning system receiver (see GPS disciplined oscillator).
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This achieves excellent short-term accuracy, with long-term accuracy equal to (and traceable to) the US national time standards.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The BIPM defines the unperturbed optical transition frequency of the hydrogen-1 neutral atom; 1,233,030,706,593,514 Hz; in terms of the caesium standard frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks based on hydrogen standards are therefore regarded as secondary representations of the second.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Hydrogen masers have superior short-term stability compared to other standards, but lower long-term accuracy.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The long-term stability of hydrogen maser standards decreases because of changes in the cavity's properties over time.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The relative error of hydrogen masers is 5 × 10−16 for periods of 1000 seconds.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This makes hydrogen masers good for radio astronomy, in particular for very long baseline interferometry.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Hydrogen masers are used for flywheel oscillators in laser-cooled atomic frequency standards and broadcasting time signals from national standards laboratories, although they need to be corrected as they drift from the correct frequency over time.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The hydrogen maser is also useful for experimental tests of the effects of special relativity and general relativity such as gravitational red shift.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Optical clocks operate similarly to microwave clocks, but at much higher frequencies, around 1015 Hz rather than the 1010 Hz range of microwave clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The advantage of optical clocks can be explained by the statement that the instability $\sigma \propto {\frac {\Delta f}{f}}{\frac {1}{S/N}}$ , where $\sigma$ is the instability, *f* is the frequency, and *S*/*N* is the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Optical clocks are based on forbidden optical transitions in ions or atoms, with a natural linewidth $\Delta f$ of typically 1 Hz, so the Q-factor is about 1015.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Compared to microwave clocks, the 105 times higher frequency gives better stability, which means that they can facilitate evaluation of lower uncertainties.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] They faster "tick" also gives better time resolution for short intervals.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Optical clocks were enabled by the development of the frequency comb, which allowed cycle-exact counting of these extremely high optical frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Optical clocks use either a single ion, or an optical lattice with 104–106 atoms.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A further variation on the optical atomic clock being developed the use of a *nuclear* energy transition (between different nuclear isomers) rather than the atomic electron transitions which current atomic clocks measure.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Most nuclear transitions operate at far too high a frequency to be measured, but the exceptionally low excitation energy of 229m Th produces "gamma rays" in the ultraviolet frequency range.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In 2003, Ekkehard Peik and Christian Tamm noted this makes a clock possible with current optical frequency-measurement techniques.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In 2012, it was shown that a nuclear clock based on a single 229 Th3+ ion could provide a total fractional frequency inaccuracy of 1.5×10−19, which was better than existing 2019 optical atomic clock technology.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Although neutral 229m Th atoms decay in microseconds by internal conversion, this pathway is energetically prohibited in 229m Th+ ions, as the second and higher ionization energy is greater than the nuclear excitation energy, giving 229m Th+ ions a long half-life on the order of 103 s.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] It is the large ratio between transition frequency and isomer lifetime which gives the clock a high quality factor.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The extremely high quality factor also makes the transition frequency very difficult to find, and the 2010s were spent searching for it.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A sufficiently precise measurement was finally achieved in 2024 as 2,020,407,384,335±2 kHz.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The first experimental optical nuclear clocks were announced in June 2026.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] They are not yet competitive with other atomic clocks, but development is expected to be rapid.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Due to its small size and the shielding effect of the surrounding electrons, an atomic nucleus is much less sensitive to ambient electromagnetic fields than is an electron in an orbital.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Because of the aforementioned insensitivity to ambient fields, it is not necessary to have the clock atoms well-separated in a dilute gas.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Current measurements take advantage of the Mössbauer effect and place the thorium ions in a solid, which allows billions of atoms to be interrogated.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In 2022, the best realisation of the second is done with caesium fountain primary standard clocks such as IT-CsF2, NIST-F2, NPL-CsF2, PTB-CSF2, SU–CsFO2 or SYRTE-FO2.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These clocks work by laser-cooling a cloud of caesium atoms to a microkelvin in a magneto-optic trap.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These cold atoms are then launched vertically by laser light.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The atoms then undergo Ramsey excitation in a microwave cavity.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The fraction of excited atoms are then detected by laser beams.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These clocks have 5×10−16 systematic uncertainty, which is equivalent to 50 picoseconds per day.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A system of several fountains worldwide contributes to International Atomic Time.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These caesium clocks also underpin optical frequency measurements.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The development of optical alomic clocks more stable than the best caesium clocks has led to proposals for redefining the second more accurately.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] However, there are several optical clock systems in active development, and it is not clear which is the best to serve as a long-term replacement for the caesium standard.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] An alternative would be to define the second by fixing the Rydberg constant to a certain value: $R_{\infty }={\frac {m_{e}e^{4}}{8\varepsilon _{0}^{2}h^{3}c}}={\frac {m_{e}c\alpha ^{2}}{2h}}$ .
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The Rydberg constant describes the energy levels in a hydrogen atom with the nonrelativistic approximation $E_{n}\approx -{\frac {R_{\infty }ch}{n^{2}}}$ .
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The only viable way to fix the Rydberg constant involves trapping and cooling hydrogen atoms.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Unfortunately, this is difficult because they are very light and move very fast, causing Doppler shifts.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The radiation needed to cool the hydrogen —121.5 nm— is also difficult to work with.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Another hurdle involves improving the uncertainty in quantum electrodynamics/QED calculations.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In the Report of the 25th meeting of the Consultative Committee for Units (2021), 3 options were considered for the redefinition of the second sometime around 2026, 2030, or 2034.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The first redefinition approach considered was a definition based on a single atomic reference transition.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The second redefinition approach considered was a definition based on a collection of frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The third redefinition approach considered was a definition based on fixing the numerical value of a fundamental constant, such as making the Rydberg constant the basis for the definition.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The committee concluded there was no feasible way to redefine the second with the third option, since no physical constant is known to enough digits currently to enable realizing the second with a constant.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A redefinition must include improved optical clock reliability.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] TAI must be contributed to by optical clocks before the BIPM affirms a redefinition.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A consistent method of communicating the resultant signals, such as fibre optics, must be developed before the second is redefined.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Representations of the second other than the SI cesium standard are motivated by the increasing accuracy of other atomic clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In particular the high frequencies and small linewidths of optical clocks promise significantly improved signal-to-noise ratio and instability.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Further secondary representations would aid in the preparation of a future redefinition of the second.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A list of frequencies recommended for secondary representations of the second is maintained by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM) since 2006 and is available online.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The list contains the frequency values and the respective standard uncertainties for the rubidium microwave transition and for several optical transitions.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] These secondary frequency standards are accurate at the level of 10−18; however, the uncertainties provided in the list are in the range 10−14 – 10−15 since they are limited by the linking to the caesium primary standard that currently (2018) defines the second.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Twenty-first century experimental atomic clocks that provide non-caesium-based secondary representations of the second are becoming so precise that they are likely to be used as extremely sensitive detectors for other things besides measuring frequency and time.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] For example, the frequency of atomic clocks is altered slightly by gravity, magnetic fields, electrical fields, force, motion, temperature and other phenomena.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The experimental clocks tend to continue to improve, and leadership in performance has shifted back and forth between various types of experimental clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The development of atomic clocks has led to many scientific and technological advances such as precise global and regional navigation satellite systems, and applications in the Internet, which depend critically on frequency and time standards.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks are installed at sites of time signal radio transmitters.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] They are used at some long-wave and medium-wave broadcasting stations to deliver a very precise carrier frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks are used in many scientific disciplines, such as for long-baseline interferometry in radio astronomy.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The Global Positioning System (GPS) operated by the United States Space Force provides very accurate timing and frequency signals.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A GPS receiver works by measuring the relative time delay of signals from a minimum of four, but usually more, GPS satellites, each of which has at least two onboard caesium and as many as two rubidium atomic clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The relative times are mathematically transformed into three absolute spatial coordinates and one absolute time coordinate.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] GPS Time (GPST) is a continuous time scale and theoretically accurate to about 14 nanoseconds.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] However, most receivers lose accuracy in the interpretation of the signals and are only accurate to 100 nanoseconds.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] GPST is related to but differs from TAI (International Atomic Time) and UTC (Coordinated Universal Time).
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] GPST remains at a constant offset from TAI (TAI – GPST = 19 seconds) and like TAI does not implement leap seconds.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Periodic corrections are performed to the on-board clocks in the satellites to keep them synchronized with ground clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The GPS navigation message includes the difference between GPST and UTC.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] As of July 2015, GPST is 17 seconds ahead of UTC because of the leap second added to UTC on 30 June 2015.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Receivers subtract this offset from GPS Time to calculate UTC.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The GLObal NAvigation Satellite System (GLONASS) operated by the Russian Aerospace Defence Forces provides an alternative to the Global Positioning System (GPS) system and is the second navigational system in operation with global coverage and of comparable precision.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] GLONASS Time (GLONASST) is generated by the GLONASS Central Synchroniser and is typically better than 1,000 nanoseconds.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Unlike GPS, the GLONASS time scale implements leap seconds, like UTC.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The Galileo Global Navigation Satellite System is operated by the European GNSS Agency and European Space Agency.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Galileo started offering global Early Operational Capability (EOC) on 15 December 2016, providing the third, and first non-military operated, global navigation satellite system.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] According to the European GNSS Agency, Galileo offers 30 nanoseconds timing accuracy.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The March 2018 Quarterly Performance Report by the European GNSS Service Centre reported the UTC Time Dissemination Service Accuracy was ≤ 7.6 nanoseconds, computed by accumulating samples over the previous 12 months, and exceeding the ≤ 30 ns target.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Each Galileo satellite has two passive hydrogen maser and two rubidium atomic clocks for onboard timing.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The Galileo navigation message includes the differences between GST, UTC and GPST, to promote interoperability.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In the summer of 2021, the European Union settled on a passive hydrogen maser for the second generation of Galileo satellites, starting in 2023, with an expected lifetime of 12 years per satellite.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The masers are about 2 feet long with a weight of 40 pounds.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The BeiDou-2/BeiDou-3 satellite navigation system is operated by the China National Space Administration.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] BeiDou Time (BDT) is a continuous time scale starting at 1 January 2006 at 0:00:00 UTC and is synchronised with UTC within 100 ns.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] BeiDou became operational in China in December 2011, with 10 satellites in use, and began offering services to customers in the Asia-Pacific region in December 2012.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] On 27 December 2018 the BeiDou Navigation Satellite System started to provide global services with a reported timing accuracy of 20 ns.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The final, 35th, BeiDou-3 satellite for global coverage was launched into orbit on 23 June 2020.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In April 2015, NASA announced that it planned to deploy a Deep Space Atomic Clock (DSAC), a miniaturized, ultra-precise mercury-ion atomic clock, into outer space.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] NASA said that the DSAC would be much more stable than other navigational clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The clock was successfully launched on 25 June 2019, activated on 23 August 2019 and deactivated two years later on 18 September 2021.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In 2022, DARPA announced a drive to upgrade to the U.S. military timekeeping systems for greater precision over time when sensors do not have access to GPS satellites, with a plan to reach precision of 1 part in 1012.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] The Robust Optical Clock Network will balance usability and accuracy as it is developed over 4 years.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A radio clock is a clock that automatically synchronizes itself by means of radio time signals received by a radio receiver.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Some manufacturers may label radio clocks as atomic clocks, because the radio signals they receive originate from atomic clocks.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Normal low-cost consumer-grade receivers that rely on the amplitude-modulated time signals have a practical accuracy uncertainty of ± 0.1 second.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] This is sufficient for many consumer applications.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Instrument grade time receivers provide higher accuracy.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Radio clocks incur a propagation delay of approximately 1 ms for every 300 kilometres (186 mi) of distance from the radio transmitter.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Many governments operate transmitters for timekeeping purposes.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] General relativity predicts that clocks tick slower deeper in a gravitational field, and this gravitational redshift effect has been well documented.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks are effective at testing general relativity on ever smaller scales.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] A project to observe twelve atomic clocks from 11 November 1999 to October 2014 resulted in a further demonstration that Einstein's theory of general relativity is accurate at small scales.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In 2021 a team of scientists at JILA measured the difference in the passage of time due to gravitational redshift between two layers of atoms separated by one millimeter using a strontium optical clock cooled to 100 nanokelvins with a precision of 7.6×10−21 seconds.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Given its quantum nature and the fact that time is a relativistic quantity, atomic clocks can be used to see how time is influenced by general relativity and quantum mechanics at the same time.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks keep accurate records of transactions between buyers and sellers to the millisecond or better, particularly in high-frequency trading.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Accurate timekeeping is needed to prevent illegal trading ahead of time, in addition to ensuring fairness to traders on the other side of the globe.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] In 2018, the then current system known as NTP is only accurate to a millisecond.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Many of the most accurate optical clocks are big and only available in large metrology labs.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Thus they are not readily useful for space-limited factories or other industrial environments that could use an atomic clock for GPS accuracy.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Researchers have designed a strontium optical lattice clock that can be moved around in an air-conditioned car trailer.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] They achieved a relative uncertainty of 7.4×10−17 compared to a stationary one.
[src:electronic-filter/atomic-clock] Manufacturers of atomic clocks in use for keeping track of UTC includes Microchip, T4Science, Anritsu, Microsemi and HP.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In physics, **attenuation** is the gradual loss of flux intensity through a medium.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] For instance, dark glasses attenuate sunlight, lead attenuates X-rays, and water and air attenuate both light and sound at variable attenuation rates.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Hearing protectors help reduce acoustic flux from flowing into the ears.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] This phenomenon is called acoustic attenuation and is measured in decibels (dBs).
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In electrical engineering and telecommunications, attenuation affects the propagation of waves and signals in electrical circuits, in optical fibers, and in air.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Electrical attenuators and optical attenuators are commonly manufactured components in this field.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In many cases, attenuation is an exponential function of the path length through the medium.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In optics and in chemical spectroscopy, this is known as the Beer–Lambert law.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In engineering, attenuation is usually measured in units of decibels per unit length of medium (dB/cm, dB/km, etc.) and is represented by the attenuation coefficient of the medium in question.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation also occurs in earthquakes; when the seismic waves move farther away from the hypocenter, they grow smaller as they are attenuated by the ground.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] One area of research in which attenuation plays a prominent role is in ultrasound physics.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation in ultrasound is the reduction in amplitude of the ultrasound beam as a function of distance through the imaging medium.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Accounting for attenuation effects in ultrasound is important because a reduced signal amplitude can affect the quality of the image produced.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] By knowing the attenuation that an ultrasound beam experiences traveling through a medium, one can adjust the input signal amplitude to compensate for any loss of energy at the desired imaging depth.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Wave equations which take acoustic attenuation into account can be written on a fractional derivative form.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In homogeneous media, the main physical properties contributing to sound attenuation are viscosity and thermal conductivity.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation coefficients are used to quantify different media according to how strongly the transmitted ultrasound amplitude decreases as a function of frequency.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation is linearly dependent on the medium length and attenuation coefficient, as well as – approximately – the frequency of the incident ultrasound beam for biological tissue (while for simpler media, such as air, the relationship is quadratic).
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation coefficients vary widely for different media.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In biomedical ultrasound imaging however, biological materials and water are the most commonly used media.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] There are two general ways of acoustic energy losses: absorption and scattering.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Ultrasound propagation through homogeneous media is associated only with absorption and can be characterized with absorption coefficient only.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Propagation through heterogeneous media requires taking into account scattering.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Shortwave radiation emitted from the Sun have wavelengths in the visible spectrum of light that range from 360 nm (violet) to 750 nm (red).
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] When the Sun's radiation reaches the sea surface, the shortwave radiation is attenuated by the water, and the intensity of light decreases exponentially with water depth.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] The intensity of light at depth can be calculated using the Beer-Lambert Law.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In clear mid-ocean waters, visible light is absorbed most strongly at the longest wavelengths.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Thus, red, orange, and yellow wavelengths are totally absorbed at shallower depths, while blue and violet wavelengths reach deeper in the water column.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Because the blue and violet wavelengths are absorbed least compared to the other wavelengths, open-ocean waters appear deep blue to the eye.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Near the shore, coastal water contains more phytoplankton than the very clear mid-ocean waters.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Chlorophyll-a pigments in the phytoplankton absorb light, and the plants themselves scatter light, making coastal waters less clear than mid-ocean waters.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Chlorophyll-a absorbs light most strongly in the shortest wavelengths (blue and violet) of the visible spectrum.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In coastal waters where high concentrations of phytoplankton occur, the green wavelength reaches the deepest in the water column and the color of water appears blue-green or green.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] The energy with which an earthquake affects a location depends on the running distance.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] The attenuation in the signal of ground motion intensity plays an important role in the assessment of possible strong groundshaking.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] A seismic wave loses energy as it propagates through the earth (**seismic attenuation**).
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] This phenomenon is tied into the dispersion of the seismic energy with the distance.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In porous fluid—saturated sedimentary rocks such as sandstones, intrinsic attenuation of seismic waves is primarily caused by the wave-induced flow of the pore fluid relative to the solid frame.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation decreases the intensity of electromagnetic radiation due to absorption or scattering of photons.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation does not include the decrease in intensity due to inverse-square law geometric spreading.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Therefore, calculation of the total change in intensity involves both the inverse-square law and an estimation of attenuation over the path.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] The primary causes of attenuation in matter are the photoelectric effect, Compton scattering, and, for photon energies of above 1.022 MeV, pair production.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] where $P_{1}$ is the input power into a 100 m long cable terminated with the nominal value of its characteristic impedance, and $P_{2}$ is the output power at the far end of this cable.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation in a coaxial cable is a function of the materials and the construction.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] The beam of X-ray is attenuated when photons are absorbed when the x-ray beam passes through the tissue.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Interaction with matter varies between high energy photons and low energy photons.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Photons travelling at higher energy are more capable of travelling through a tissue specimen as they have less chances of interacting with matter.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] This is mainly due to the photoelectric effect which states that "the probability of photoelectric absorption is approximately proportional to (Z/E)3, where Z is the atomic number of the tissue atom and E is the photon energy.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In context of this, an increase in photon energy (E) will result in a rapid decrease in the interaction with matter.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In CT imaging, attenuation describes the density or darkness of the image.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation in fiber optics, also known as transmission loss, is the reduction in intensity of the light beam (or signal) with respect to distance travelled through a transmission medium.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation coefficients in fiber optics usually use units of dB/km through the medium due to the relatively high quality of transparency of modern optical transmission.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] The medium is typically a fiber of silica glass that confines the incident light beam to the inside.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation is an important factor limiting the transmission of a digital signal across large distances.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Thus, much research has gone into both limiting the attenuation and maximizing the amplification of the optical signal.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Empirical research has shown that attenuation in optical fiber is caused primarily by both scattering and absorption.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] The propagation of light through the core of an optical fiber is based on total internal reflection of the lightwave.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Rough and irregular surfaces, even at the molecular level of the glass, can cause light rays to be reflected in many random directions.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] This type of reflection is referred to as "diffuse reflection", and it is typically characterized by wide variety of reflection angles.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Most objects that can be seen with the naked eye are visible due to diffuse reflection.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Another term commonly used for this type of reflection is "light scattering".
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Light scattering from the surfaces of objects is our primary mechanism of physical observation.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Light scattering from many common surfaces can be modelled by reflectance.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Light scattering depends on the wavelength of the light being scattered.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Thus, limits to spatial scales of visibility arise, depending on the frequency of the incident lightwave and the physical dimension (or spatial scale) of the scattering center, which is typically in the form of some specific microstructural feature.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] For example, since visible light has a wavelength scale on the order of one micrometer, scattering centers will have dimensions on a similar spatial scale.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Thus, attenuation results from the incoherent scattering of light at internal surfaces and interfaces.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In (poly)crystalline materials such as metals and ceramics, in addition to pores, most of the internal surfaces or interfaces are in the form of grain boundaries that separate tiny regions of crystalline order.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] It has recently been shown that, when the size of the scattering center (or grain boundary) is reduced below the size of the wavelength of the light being scattered, the scattering no longer occurs to any significant extent.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] This phenomenon has given rise to the production of transparent ceramic materials.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Likewise, the scattering of light in optical quality glass fiber is caused by molecular-level irregularities (compositional fluctuations) in the glass structure.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Indeed, one emerging school of thought is that a glass is simply the limiting case of a polycrystalline solid.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Within this framework, "domains" exhibiting various degrees of short-range order become the building-blocks of both metals and alloys, as well as glasses and ceramics.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Distributed both between and within these domains are microstructural defects that will provide the most ideal locations for the occurrence of light scattering.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] This same phenomenon is seen as one of the limiting factors in the transparency of IR missile domes.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In addition to light scattering, attenuation or signal loss can also occur due to selective absorption of specific wavelengths, in a manner similar to that responsible for the appearance of color.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] The selective absorption of infrared (IR) light by a particular material occurs because the selected frequency of the light wave matches the frequency (or an integral multiple of the frequency) at which the particles of that material vibrate.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Since different atoms and molecules have different natural frequencies of vibration, they will selectively absorb different frequencies (or portions of the spectrum) of infrared (IR) light.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In optical fibers, attenuation is the rate at which the signal light decreases in intensity.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] For this reason, glass fiber (which has a low attenuation) is used for long-distance fiber optic cables; plastic fiber has a higher attenuation and, hence, shorter range.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] There also exist optical attenuators that decrease the signal in a fiber optic cable intentionally.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation of light is also important in physical oceanography.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] This same effect is an important consideration in weather radar, as raindrops absorb a part of the emitted beam that is more or less significant, depending on the wavelength used.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Due to the damaging effects of high-energy photons, it is necessary to know how much energy is deposited in tissue during diagnostic treatments involving such radiation.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In addition, gamma radiation is used in cancer treatments where it is important to know how much energy will be deposited in healthy and in tumorous tissue.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] In computer graphics attenuation defines the local or global influence of light sources and force fields.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation is an important consideration in the modern world of wireless telecommunications.
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] Attenuation limits the range of radio signals and is affected by the materials a signal must travel through (e.g., air, wood, concrete, rain).
[src:electronic-filter/attenuation] See the article on path loss for more information on signal loss in wireless communication.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Electronic filters remove unwanted frequency components from the applied signal, enhance wanted ones, or both.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The most common types of electronic filters are linear filters, regardless of other aspects of their design.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] See the article on linear filters for details on their design and analysis.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The oldest forms of electronic filters are passive analog linear filters, constructed using only resistors and capacitors or resistors and inductors.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] These are known as RC and RL single-pole filters respectively.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] However, these simple filters have very limited uses.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Multipole LC filters provide greater control of response form, bandwidth and transition bands.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The first of these filters was the constant k filter, invented by George Campbell in 1910.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Campbell's filter was a ladder network based on transmission line theory.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Together with improved filters by Otto Zobel and others, these filters are known as image parameter filters.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] A major step forward was taken by Wilhelm Cauer who founded the field of network synthesis around the time of World War II.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Cauer's theory allowed filters to be constructed that precisely followed some prescribed frequency function.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Passive implementations of linear filters are based on combinations of resistors (R), inductors (L) and capacitors (C).
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] These types are collectively known as *passive filters*, because they do not depend upon an external power supply and they do not contain active components such as transistors.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Inductors block high-frequency signals and conduct low-frequency signals, while capacitors do the reverse.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] A filter in which the signal passes through an inductor, or in which a capacitor provides a path to ground, presents less attenuation to low-frequency signals than high-frequency signals and is therefore a *low-pass filter*.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] If the signal passes through a capacitor, or has a path to ground through an inductor, then the filter presents less attenuation to high-frequency signals than low-frequency signals and therefore is a *high-pass filter*.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Resistors on their own have no frequency-selective properties, but are added to inductors and capacitors to determine the *time-constants* of the circuit, and therefore the frequencies to which it responds.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The inductors and capacitors are the reactive elements of the filter.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The number of elements determines the order of the filter.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] In this context, an LC tuned circuit being used in a band-pass or band-stop filter is considered a single element even though it consists of two components.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] At high frequencies (above about 100 megahertz), sometimes the inductors consist of single loops or strips of sheet metal, and the capacitors consist of adjacent strips of metal.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] These inductive or capacitive pieces of metal are called stubs.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The simplest passive filters, RC and RL filters, include only one reactive element, except for the hybrid LC filter, which is characterized by inductance and capacitance integrated in one element.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] An L filter consists of two reactive elements, one in series and one in parallel.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Three-element filters can have a 'T' or 'π' topology and in either geometries, a low-pass, high-pass, band-pass, or band-stop characteristic is possible.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The components can be chosen symmetric or not, depending on the required frequency characteristics.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The high-pass T filter in the illustration, has a very low impedance at high frequencies, and a very high impedance at low frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] That means that it can be inserted in a transmission line, resulting in the high frequencies being passed and low frequencies being reflected.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Likewise, for the illustrated low-pass π filter, the circuit can be connected to a transmission line, transmitting low frequencies and reflecting high frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Using m-derived filter sections with correct termination impedances, the input impedance can be reasonably constant in the pass band.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Multiple-element filtration are usually constructed as a ladder network.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] These can be seen as a continuation of the L,T and π designs of filters.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] More elements are needed when it is desired to improve some parameter of the filter such as stop-band rejection or slope of transition from pass-band to stop-band.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Reflectionless filters are passive structures that in principle have identically zero reflection coefficient at all frequencies.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Such structures may be synthesized with lumped inductors, capacitors, and resistors, or by transmission lines and resistors.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Active filters are implemented using a combination of passive and active (amplifying) components, and require an outside power source.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Operational amplifiers are frequently used in active filter designs.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] These can have high Q factor, and can achieve resonance without the use of inductors.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] However, their upper frequency limit is limited by the bandwidth of the amplifiers.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] There are many filter technologies other than lumped component electronics.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] These include digital filters, crystal filters, mechanical filters, surface acoustic wave (SAW) filters, thin-film bulk acoustic resonator (TFBAR, FBAR) based filters, garnet filters, and atomic filters (used in atomic clocks).
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The transfer function of all linear time-invariant filters, when constructed of lumped components (as opposed to distributed components such as transmission lines), will be the ratio of two polynomials in s , i.e. a rational function of $\ s$ .
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The order of the transfer function will be the highest power of $\ s$ encountered in either the numerator or the denominator.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Electronic filters can be classified by the technology used to implement them.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Filters using passive filter and active filter technology can be further classified by the particular electronic filter topology used to implement them.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Any given filter transfer function may be implemented in any electronic filter topology.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Historically, linear analog filter design has evolved through three major approaches.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The oldest designs are simple circuits where the main design criterion was the Q factor of the circuit.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] This reflected the radio receiver application of filtering as Q was a measure of the frequency selectivity of a tuning circuit.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] From the 1920s filters began to be designed from the image point of view, mostly being driven by the requirements of telecommunications.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] After World War II the dominant methodology was network synthesis.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The higher mathematics used originally required extensive tables of polynomial coefficient values to be published but modern computer resources have made that unnecessary.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Low order filters can be designed by directly applying basic circuit laws such as Kirchhoff's laws to obtain the transfer function.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] This kind of analysis is usually only carried out for simple filters of 1st or 2nd order.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] This approach analyses the filter sections from the point of view of the filter being in an infinite chain of identical sections.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] It has the advantages of simplicity of approach and the ability to easily extend to higher orders.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] It has the disadvantage that accuracy of predicted responses relies on filter terminations in the image impedance, which is usually not the case.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The network synthesis approach starts with a required transfer function and then expresses that as a polynomial equation of the input impedance of the filter.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The actual element values of the filter are obtained by continued-fraction or partial-fraction expansions of this polynomial.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Unlike the image method, there is no need for impedance matching networks at the terminations as the effects of the terminating resistors are included in the analysis from the start.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] Here is an image comparing Butterworth, Chebyshev, and elliptic filters.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The filters in this illustration are all fifth-order low-pass filters.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] The particular implementation – analog or digital, passive or active – makes no difference; their output would be the same.
[src:electronic-filter/electronic-filter] As is clear from the image, elliptic filters are sharper than all the others, but they show ripples on the whole bandwidth.
